│ `VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute`.                            │
│ 2.  The crash happens at the line: `StartIdx0 =              │
│ Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);`                  │
│ 3.  Using the debugger, we find the following types:         │
│     *   `StartIdx0->getType()` is `i32`.                     │
│     *   `IntStepTy` is also `i32`.                           │
│                                                              │
│ The code is attempting to create a `trunc` instruction where │
│ both the source and destination types are `i32`. A           │
│ truncation is only valid if the source type has a larger bit │
│ width than the destination type. Since `i32` is not wider    │
│ than `i32`, `CastInst::castIsValid` returns `false`, and the │
│ assertion fails.                                             │
│                                                              │
│ This situation arises because the `VPScalarIVStepsRecipe` is │
│ designed to handle induction variables where the index might │
│ be of a wider type (like `i64` from pointer arithmetic) than │
│ the step value's type. The recipe unconditionally adds a     │
│ `trunc` to match the types. However, in this specific case,  │
│ the induction variable `%i` is an `i32`, and all related     │
│ calculations remain within `i32`. The `StartIdx` for the     │
│ recipe is derived from this `i32` induction variable, and    │
│ the step type is also `i32`. The unconditional truncation is │
│ therefore incorrect.                                         │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to make the truncation conditional. It should     │
│ only be performed if the bit width of the start index's type │
│ is actually greater than the bit width of the step type.     │
│                                                              │
│ ### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)                                │
│                                                              │
│ The issue lies in `VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute` where an  │
│ unconditional truncation is performed.                       │
│                                                              │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ // llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp            │
│                                                              │
│ void VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute(VPTransformState &State) │
│ {                                                            │
│   // ... (existing code)                                     │
│   Value *StartIdx0 = getOperand(0)->getLiveInIRValue(State); │
│   Value *Step = getOperand(1)->getLiveInIRValue(State);      │
│   // ... (existing code)                                     │
│   Type *IntStepTy = Step->getType();                         │
│   if (isa<VectorType>(IntStepTy))                            │
│     IntStepTy =                                              │
│ cast<VectorType>(IntStepTy)->getElementType();               │
│                                                              │
│   // The start index may have a wider type than the step     │
│ value. Truncate it to                                        │
│   // the same type.                                          │
│   StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);     │
│                                                              │
│   // ... (rest of the function)                              │
│ }                                                            │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ The `CreateTrunc` call needs to be guarded.                  │
│                                                              │
│ **File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp`   │
│ **Edit Point**:                                              │
│                                                              │
│ ```diff                                                      │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp         │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp         │
│ @@ -2126,8 +2126,9 @@                                        │
│                                                              │
│    // The start index may have a wider type than the step    │
│ value. Truncate it to                                        │
│    // the same type.                                         │
│ -  StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);    │
│ -                                                            │
│ +  if (StartIdx0->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits() >         │
│ +      IntStepTy->getScalarSizeInBits())                     │
│ +    StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);  │
│    for (unsigned Part = 0; Part < UF; ++Part) {              │
│      for (unsigned Lane = 0; Lane < VF; ++Lane) {            │
│        Value *CurrentStep = Builder.CreateAdd(               │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
│                                                              │
│ This change ensures that the `trunc` is only inserted when   │
│ it is a valid and necessary operation, i.e., when the source │
│ type is wider than the destination type.                     │
│                                                              │
│ ### 5. Conclusion                                            │
│                                                              │
│ The root cause of the crash is an incorrect unconditional    │
│ `trunc` instruction being generated by                       │
│ `VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute`. The recipe did not account │
│ for cases where the start index and step value for the       │
│ induction have the same type, leading to an attempt to       │
│ create an invalid `trunc i32 to i32` cast. By adding a       │
│ condition to only perform the truncation when the source     │
│ type is wider than the destination, we fix the assertion     │
│ failure and allow the vectorizer to correctly generate code  │
│ for this and similar cases.                                  │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------              │
