  "reason_thou": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe crash
occurs due to an assertion failure in
`llvm::ConstantExpr::getCast`, which is triggered when
`IRBuilder::CreateTrunc` attempts to constant-fold an invalid
truncation. The backtrace indicates this happens within
`VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute`. This recipe is used to
generate a sequence of scalar instructions that represent a
vector operation, often for induction variables or
reductions.\n\nThe assertion `CastInst::castIsValid(opc, C, Ty)`
fails, meaning we are trying to create a `trunc` constant
expression from a constant `C` to a type `Ty` where this
operation is illegal. Specifically, this happens when the bit
width of the source type is not greater than the bit width of
the destination type.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log\n\nThe
`opt` log shows that the loop vectorizer decides to apply loop
interleaving with an unroll factor (UF) of 8 and a vectorization
factor (VF) of 1. This is essentially unrolling the loop 8
times.\n\nThe final VPlan includes a `SCALAR-STEPS`
recipe:\n```\nvp<%2> = SCALAR-STEPS vp<%1>, ir<%x>, ir<1>,
ir<7>\n```\nThis recipe is responsible for generating the
unrolled scalar code for the reduction on `%sum`. The arguments
are the start value, the step value, the number of lanes (VF),
and the number of unrolled parts (UF).\n\nThe crash happens
during the execution of this VPlan, specifically when
materializing the code for the `SCALAR-STEPS` recipe.\n\n### 3.
Root Cause Analysis\n\nBy inspecting the state in the debugger,
we can pinpoint the exact cause.\n\n1.  The execution is inside
`VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute`.\n2.  The crash happens at the
line: `StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0,
IntStepTy);`\n3.  Using the debugger, we find the following
types:\n    *   `StartIdx0->getType()` is `i32`.\n    *
`IntStepTy` is also `i32`.\n\nThe code is attempting to create a
`trunc` instruction where both the source and destination types
are `i32`. A truncation is only valid if the source type has a
larger bit width than the destination type. Since `i32` is not
wider than `i32`, `CastInst::castIsValid` returns `false`, and
the assertion fails.\n\nThis situation arises because the
`VPScalarIVStepsRecipe` is designed to handle induction
variables where the index might be of a wider type (like `i64`
from pointer arithmetic) than the step value's type. The recipe
unconditionally adds a `trunc` to match the types. However, in
this specific case, the induction variable `%i` is an `i32`, and
all related calculations remain within `i32`. The `StartIdx` for
the recipe is derived from this `i32` induction variable, and
the step type is also `i32`. The unconditional truncation is
therefore incorrect.\n\nThe fix is to make the truncation
conditional. It should only be performed if the bit width of the
start index's type is actually greater than the bit width of the
step type.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe issue lies in
`VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute` where an unconditional
truncation is performed.\n\n```cpp\n//
llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp\n\nvoid
VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute(VPTransformState &State) {\n  //
... (existing code)\n  Value *StartIdx0 =
getOperand(0)->getLiveInIRValue(State);\n  Value *Step =
getOperand(1)->getLiveInIRValue(State);\n  // ... (existing
code)\n  Type *IntStepTy = Step->getType();\n  if
(isa<VectorType>(IntStepTy))\n    IntStepTy =
cast<VectorType>(IntStepTy)->getElementType();\n\n  // The start
index may have a wider type than the step value. Truncate it
to\n  // the same type.\n  StartIdx0 =
Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);\n\n  // ... (rest of
the function)\n}\n```\n\nThe `CreateTrunc` call needs to be
guarded.\n\n**File**:
`llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp`\n**Edit
Point**:\n\n```diff\n---
a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp\n+++
b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/VPlanRecipes.cpp\n@@ -2126,8
+2126,9 @@\n \n   // The start index may have a wider type than
the step value. Truncate it to\n   // the same type.\n-
StartIdx0 = Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);\n-\n+  if
(StartIdx0->getType()->getScalarSizeInBits() >\n+
IntStepTy->getScalarSizeInBits())\n+    StartIdx0 =
Builder.CreateTrunc(StartIdx0, IntStepTy);\n   for (unsigned
Part = 0; Part < UF; ++Part) {\n     for (unsigned Lane = 0;
Lane < VF; ++Lane) {\n       Value *CurrentStep =
Builder.CreateAdd(\n\n```\n\nThis change ensures that the
`trunc` is only inserted when it is a valid and necessary
operation, i.e., when the source type is wider than the
destination type.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe root cause of the
crash is an incorrect unconditional `trunc` instruction being
generated by `VPScalarIVStepsRecipe::execute`. The recipe did
not account for cases where the start index and step value for
the induction have the same type, leading to an attempt to
create an invalid `trunc i32 to i32` cast. By adding a condition
to only perform the truncation when the source type is wider
than the destination, we fix the assertion failure and allow the
vectorizer to correctly generate code for this and similar
cases.",
